{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CoP2XnymWFkgdfo6zkLAKC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: The generated reply references specific points from the incoming email rather than producing a generic response.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about what the LLM generates — does it actually reference specific points from the email? This is about LLM output quality.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes, this depends on what the real LLM produces. A stub would always return the same thing — you'd just be testing your stub. To verify the LLM actually incorporates email content, you need a real LLM call.\n- MULTI-STEP: Not multiple agentic steps — just the generation step.\n\n\n- Minimum level: **Agentic**\n\n**Behavior 2: The factual consistency check flags claims in the draft that contradict entries in the knowledge base.**\n\nFor the consistency checker, I need to determine whether it's rule-based or LLM-powered. If it's deterministic logic comparing draft claims against KB entries, that's testable with mocks. But if it relies on an LLM to evaluate semantic consistency, then I'd need a real LLM call to properly verify the behavior.\n\nGiven this is an autonomous email assistant built on LLMs, the consistency check almost certainly uses an LLM for semantic comparison rather than simple pattern matching. That means mocking it would hide real failures, so I'm going with Agentic.\n\nFor the knowledge base disclaimer behavior, the key question is whether the LLM actually includes disclaimers when it gets empty results. A stubbed KB would always return whatever you programmed it to, so you'd never catch cases where the real LLM fabricates instead of disclaiming.\n\nFor the approval workflow, the blocking logic is pure orchestration — whether a draft gets sent depends on user approval state, not LLM decisions. The actual email sending would need real infrastructure, but the test is really about whether the system prevents sending without approval.\n\nBehavior 5 is clearly a workflow test since it chains multiple agentic steps together: reading the thread, generating a draft with the LLM, fact-checking, and presenting for approval.\n\nSo my final categorization is: the first three behaviors are Agentic, the approval workflow is Integration, and the full end-to-end sequence is Workflow.\n\nNow I'm assigning probability distributions across test levels for each behavior. Behavior 1 (contextually appropriate reply generation) is almost certainly Agentic at 0.85 probability, with minimal chance of being Unit or System. Behavior 2 (consistency checking) leans Agentic at 0.75 but has a higher Integration probability at 0.15 since the KB lookup could be deterministic. I'm working through the probabilities for Behavior 3 next.\n\nFor Behavior 4, the approval gate function is actually testable at the Unit level with 0.20 probability, and Integration jumps to 0.65 since this is where the logic really lives. Behavior 5 is almost entirely Workflow-dependent at 0.85, which makes sense for a multi-step pipeline.\n\nI'm reconsidering Behavior 2 more carefully — the consistency checker in an LLM drafting context is probably itself implemented with an LLM, so I need to think about what that means for the test strategy. For behavior 4, I need to reconsider whether Unit testing is enough — since the approval state and send action interact across multiple modules, Integration testing is the better fit to verify that the workflow actually blocks sending without approval. Now I'm ready to write out the test descriptions.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9810,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9810},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"05ebfa9b-9cc0-4a3d-bc35-14ed11fa21bb","uuid":"5953b183-ace9-4aba-ae0d-cc870a5b229a"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CoP2XnymWFkgdfo6zkLAKC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_015JPNRHRR1ca1o1CUv4S8Ks","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated reply references specific points from the incoming email rather than producing a generic response.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure — generating a generic reply that ignores the email's content — only manifests when a real LLM processes the actual email thread. LLM-DEP: A stub always returns the same pre-programmed response, so a test with a stub never verifies that the LLM actually grounds its reply in the incoming email's specifics. Whether the model references particular points depends on the model's actual behavior and the prompt design, not on deterministic code logic. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the LLM would make this test trivially pass (the stub always 'references' whatever you hard-code), permanently hiding prompt-design or context-window failures. REJECTION-GATE: Integration is disqualified because no amount of in-process module wiring can substitute for observing what the real model actually generates in response to a real email.","test_description":"Feed a real incoming email thread with 3–4 distinct named claims or questions into the drafting pipeline with a live LLM call. Assert that the generated draft explicitly addresses at least those named claims or questions by keyword or semantic match, and does not return a boilerplate reply lacking those specifics.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.83,"Workflow":0.07}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The factual consistency check flags claims in the draft that contradict entries in the knowledge base.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: A factual consistency checker in an LLM-based assistant is itself typically LLM-driven (semantic entailment or contradiction detection), meaning its correctness depends on the model's actual classification decisions. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing the checker always returns a fixed 'flagged/not-flagged' result, hiding failures where the real model misses subtle contradictions or is confused by paraphrase. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: Even if the checker were implemented as deterministic string-matching, the behavior asserts semantic contradiction detection — the kind of match that varies across KB phrasing, paraphrase, and negation, and that only a real ML/LLM call can evaluate faithfully. REJECTION-GATE: Integration would be sufficient only if the checker were a deterministic lookup — nothing in the behavior description disqualifies an LLM-backed semantic contradiction detector.","test_description":"Construct a draft that contains at least two claims: one that directly contradicts a KB entry and one that agrees with a KB entry. Run the real consistency-check step against the real KB. Assert the contradicting claim is flagged and the agreeing claim is not flagged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the knowledge base has no relevant entries, the draft includes a disclaimer rather than fabricating facts.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: Whether the LLM includes a disclaimer when it receives no KB context is entirely a function of the model's instruction-following and behavior — it is an LLM steering test. MOCK-HIDE: A stub always returns what you hard-code; testing with a stub merely confirms the stub respects the disclaimer, not that the real model does. MOCK-MISS: The failure mode (model fabricates rather than disclaims) is invisible without a real model call, because the stub never hallucinates. REJECTION-GATE: Integration is disqualified because an in-process fake for the LLM cannot reproduce the real model's tendency to confabulate facts when context is absent — that is precisely what the behavior is designed to detect.","test_description":"Supply an empty KB (zero relevant entries returned) and a real email thread asking a factual question. Run the draft generation step with a real LLM call. Assert the resulting draft contains a disclaimer phrase (e.g., 'I don't have information on…' or 'I cannot confirm…') and does not assert the queried fact as true.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The approval workflow blocks sending until the user explicitly approves — no draft is sent automatically.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure — accidental auto-send — only surfaces when the approval gate module and the email-send module are wired together; a unit test of the gate function in isolation cannot confirm the send path is actually gated. LLM-DEP: The approval gate is pure control-flow logic — whether a send is permitted depends on a user-provided boolean state, not on any LLM decision. No real model output is needed. REAL-INFRA: The behavior is about blocking, not actual mail delivery; an in-process stub for the email sender is sufficient to verify the send function is never invoked without approval. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network required — a spy/stub on the send module suffices. (b) No AI/ML output involved. (c) No chained agentic steps. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic is disqualified because the correctness of the approval gate does not depend on what a model returns.","test_description":"Wire together the draft-presenter module and the email-send module with a spy replacing the actual send transport. (1) Trigger the pipeline up to the approval-presentation step without providing user approval — assert the spy was never called. (2) Provide explicit user approval — assert the spy is called exactly once. Confirm no timing or background task bypasses the gate.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.06,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full sequence — read thread, generate draft, check facts, present for approval — works end-to-end for a real email thread.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The behavior explicitly names a sequence of four distinct stages, at least two of which (generate draft, check facts) involve real LLM/ML model decisions whose outputs govern the next stage's input. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing any stage breaks the chain: a stubbed generator hides prompt/context failures; a stubbed checker hides consistency-detection failures; context or state lost between stages (e.g., KB context not carried into the consistency check) is invisible unless all stages are real. LLM-DEP: Both generation and consistency-checking depend on real model output, so the minimum for each individually is Agentic — sequencing them elevates to Workflow. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic (single step) is disqualified by the explicit multi-step chain enumerated in the behavior description. Integration is disqualified because at least two stages depend on real LLM output.","test_description":"Run the complete pipeline end-to-end against a real email thread using live LLM calls: (1) read and parse the thread, (2) generate a draft, (3) run the factual consistency check against a real KB with at least one contradicting entry, (4) present for approval. Assert: draft is non-empty and addresses thread content, the contradicting claim is flagged in the consistency report, the approval gate holds (send spy not invoked), and the system surfaces the draft for user review.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.06,"Workflow":0.88}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9810,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9810},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"05ebfa9b-9cc0-4a3d-bc35-14ed11fa21bb","uuid":"77a33d0a-7fa3-4e79-bdb3-85c6bde77cd3"}
